✅ Expert-Level On-Page SEO Checklist
being an expert seo master, please follow all the parts while developing a feature

Part 1: Strategic & Foundational Blueprint

1.1 Align with User Intent & Semantic SEO

Target informational + transactional intent: "How much does carpet cleaning cost?", "Best carpet cleaners near me", "Professional carpet cleaning Manchester".

Build keyword clusters: primary ("carpet cleaning Manchester", "professional carpet cleaners near me") + related ("carpet steam cleaning", "upholstery cleaning Manchester", "rug cleaning near me").

Benchmark SERPs & identify information gain: competitors often have thin FAQs → create deeper step-by-step guides, before/after galleries, and pricing calculators.

Ensure people-first content: add original data (customer reviews, average cleaning times, service area coverage maps).

1.2 Demonstrate E-E-A-T

Add author bio ("Carpet Cleaning Specialist"), company credentials (IICRC certified, years in business), and case studies/testimonials.

Build About, Contact, Privacy Policy pages for trust signals.

Link to authoritative sources: IICRC, NCCA, industry associations.

Implement Author + Organization Schema.

Add "Last Updated" date (critical: LLMs and Google's AI Overviews reward freshness).

Part 2: Core Technical Implementation

2.1 URL & Site Structure

Create clean URLs:

/carpet-cleaning

/upholstery-cleaning

/rug-cleaning

/mattress-cleaning

/areas/manchester

/areas/trafford

Use HTTPS only, redirect non-preferred versions.

Add breadcrumb schema.

2.2 Crawlability & Indexability

In robots.txt, allow Bingbot + GPTBot (for Copilot + GPT discovery).

Add to XML sitemap + IndexNow for instant Bing push.

Validate in GSC + Bing Webmaster Tools.

2.3 Canonicalization & Duplicate Content

Use canonical tags (point to self).

Manage UTM/params.

Add hreflang if multi-region (UK vs. other).

2.4 Internal Linking

Each key page (Services / Areas / Reviews) should get 3+ contextual links.

Use descriptive anchors ("carpet cleaning in Manchester", "professional upholstery cleaning", "rug cleaning near me").

Avoid orphan pages.

Part 3: On-Page Content & Elements

3.1 Title & Meta Description

Titles:

"Carpet Cleaning Manchester | Professional Service | Fresh Fiber"

Keep <60 chars, keyword front-loaded.

Meta descriptions: compelling, <155 chars, with CTA:

"Expert carpet cleaning in Manchester. Same-day service, eco-friendly methods, 100% satisfaction guarantee. Get your free quote in 60 seconds."

3.2 Heading Structure

H1: "Professional Carpet Cleaning in Manchester"

H2s: "Our Cleaning Services", "Why Choose Fresh Fiber", "Areas We Cover", "What Our Customers Say".

3.3 Visual & Media Optimization

Use WebP images (before/after photos, cleaning process).

Alt text with keywords ("Professional carpet cleaning service in Manchester living room").

If using video (cleaning process), add VideoObject schema.

3.4 Readability & Formatting

Start with 2–3 sentence TL;DR per page (LLMs quote this first).

Short paras, bullet lists, bold takeaways.

Add FAQ section (FAQPage schema).

Part 4: Page Experience & Performance

4.1 Core Web Vitals

LCP: preload hero assets (form/CTA visible in <2.5s).

INP: minimize JS (especially eligibility checker).

CLS: reserve space for banners/forms.

4.2 UX & Accessibility

Mobile-first, ARIA roles, high contrast.

Table of contents with jump links → LLMs & users can navigate sections quickly.

4.3 Security & Trust Signals

HTTPS only.

Trust badges (IICRC Certified, NCCA Member, Insurance).

Reviews/testimonials on LocalBusiness schema.

Part 5: Structured Data for Enhanced Visibility

5.1 Schema Strategy

Use JSON-LD only.

Core types:

Organization (with logo + contact info).

FAQPage (eligibility, application timelines).

HowTo (application steps).

LocalBusiness (if regional).

BreadcrumbList.

5.2 AI & SERP Optimization

Explicitly map entities to Knowledge Graph: "Fresh Fiber Carpet Cleaning" → local business entity, "carpet cleaning Manchester" → service + location.

Optimize FAQs for AI Overviews (short, declarative answers).

Add "speakable" schema for voice queries ("How much does carpet cleaning cost?", "Best carpet cleaners near me").

**Speakable Schema Implementation:**

Create a SpeakableSpecification schema to identify content sections suitable for text-to-speech (TTS) output on Google Assistant, Siri, Alexa, and other voice assistants:

```typescript
// src/components/structured-data/SpeakableSchema.tsx
interface SpeakableSchemaProps {
  serviceName: string
  shortDescription: string
  priceFrom: string
}

export function SpeakableSchema({ serviceName, shortDescription, priceFrom }: SpeakableSchemaProps) {
  const schema = {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'WebPage',
    name: `${serviceName} Manchester`,
    description: `${shortDescription}. Professional service in Manchester with same-day availability. Prices from ${priceFrom}.`,
    speakable: {
      '@type': 'SpeakableSpecification',
      cssSelector: [
        '.speakable-headline',     // H1 service name
        '.speakable-tldr',         // TL;DR summary
        '.speakable-pricing',      // Pricing information
        '.speakable-cta',          // Call to action
      ],
      // Alternative: use XPath selectors
      xpath: [
        '/html/head/title',
        "//h1[@class='speakable-headline']",
        "//div[@class='speakable-tldr']",
      ],
    },
  };

  return (
    <script
      type="application/ld+json"
      dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(schema) }}
    />
  );
}
```

